I’ve tried about 80% of the pho places in SF and I have to say that Golden King is now my new favorite (used to be Turtle Tower). I order from here a few times a week and get the Pho Dac Biet. The service is super fast and the pho broth and meat is so good!!

I believe this place is more Chinese than Vietnamese. Decided to try based on several Yelp reviews claiming it's the best Vietnamese beef stew in the Bay Area. It's ok. Chunks of beef were tender, but it was missing chunks of tendon and carrot. The broth tasted ok, but not really like Vietnamese-style broth.

Clean place including restroom.  Generous portion of freshly prepared food.  Tasty and filling for not much money.  Free hot tea.  Nice people, too.  A Chinatown gem!  It doesn't get any more authentic!

This place has the best Pho I've ever had in the Chinatown area. Their Dac Biet is the best when it comes to Pho. The noodles are cooked to perfection, their meats are thinly sliced, lots of beef flanks and their soup base is spectacular! I'm defiantly a returning customer (Mostly at lunch time)!

Relatively cheap Vietnamese food in San Francisco. Taste of pho noodles was not too bad, but I wish they had proper flat glass noodles. As with all the shops in Chinatown, it's somewhat eccentric and dated, but exotic I guess. Much cheaper than all the expensive meals out at Union Square.

We ate here twice so far in 5 days and the owners recognized us. Very friendly and gave helpful suggestions when choosing from the menu. My kids like the food and more importantly, I don't feel very thirsty after eating here like I often do when I eat at other Chinese restaurants in Chinatown. I'm sure we'll come here again.

If you're in chinatown, but you're craving vietnamese food instead of chinese, you should come here. Their food is pretty good for being in chinatown. My friends always come here whenever we want to catch up. The inside may look a little old, but its kind of the norm for a restuarant in chinatown.
The broth and meatballs are good. The lean beef is pretty tough though. And the noodles get soggy pretty quickly. I prefer golden star around the corner.
